# Menu-bar (tray) app

The app is a macOS **menu-bar app** (no Dock icon). This is the primary reason idle
memory/CPU is low: **no window is created at startup**, so no webview process runs until
the user opens one.

## Windows are created on demand (and destroyed on close)

- `tauri.conf.json` has `"windows": []` — nothing auto-opens. The app is set to
  `ActivationPolicy::Accessory` in `setup` (no Dock icon).
- Two window labels, both built lazily via `WebviewWindowBuilder`:
  - **`popover`** (`popover.html` / `src/popover.ts`) — a small, borderless, always-on-top
    quick-glance window: current lap + today's total, Pause/Resume, New Lap, and Expand.
    Built by `toggle_popover()` on left-click of the tray, positioned under the icon, and
    it **closes itself on blur** (`WindowEvent::Focused(false)`).
  - **`main`** (`index.html` / `src/main.ts`) — the full UI (laps + history). Built by
    `open_main_window()` from the popover's Expand button or the tray's Open menu item.
- Closing a window destroys its webview, reclaiming memory. Reopening rebuilds it.
- Because all windows can be closed, the app must NOT quit when the last one closes:
  `run()` uses `.build().run(|_, event| { if ExitRequested { api.prevent_exit() } })`.
  The only real quit path is the tray menu's **Quit** item (`app.exit(0)`).

## Tray

- Built in `setup` with `TrayIconBuilder` (id `"tray"`), icon from `icons/32x32.png`.
- Left click → `toggle_popover()` (via `on_tray_icon_event`, filtered to
  `MouseButton::Left` + `MouseButtonState::Up`). `show_menu_on_left_click(false)` so the
  left click doesn't open the right-click menu.
- Right-click menu (`on_menu_event`): `open` → `open_main_window`, `quit` → `app.exit(0)`.
- Requires `tauri = { features = ["tray-icon", "image-png"] }` and both window labels listed
  in `capabilities/default.json` (`"windows": ["main", "popover"]`).

## The timer is on-demand, never a background counter

- There is **no always-running timer**. Elapsed time is derived from stored timestamps
  (`now - current_lap_start_timestamp`) and only computed while a window is open and
  polling (popover polls every 1s, full window every 200ms). Close the window and the
  polling stops with the webview.
- Lock/sleep detection threads DO run continuously — that is deliberate and required:
  they finalize the current lap on lock/sleep and start a new one on unlock/wake, which is
  what makes "now - start" accurate (locked/asleep/off time is excluded, not counted).

## Multi-page frontend

- `vite.config.ts` declares two entry points: `index.html` (main) and `popover.html`.
- Keep `popover.ts` minimal — it's a glance view. Rich detail/history belongs in the full
  window (`main.ts`). Both share the `CurrentStatus` shape from the backend.
